1/* Dictionary object implementation using a hash table */
2

4 describing explorations into dictionary design and optimization.
5 It covers typical dictionary use patterns, the parameters for

9/* PyDictKeysObject
10
11This implements the dictionary's hashtable.
12
13As of Python 3.6, this is compact and ordered. Basic idea is described here:
14* https://mail.python.org/pipermail/python-dev/2012-December/123028.html
15* https://morepypy.blogspot.com/2015/01/faster-more-memory-efficient-and-more.html
16
17layout:
18
19+---------------+
20| dk_refcnt |
21| dk_size |
22| dk_lookup |
23| dk_usable |
24| dk_nentries |
25+---------------+
26| dk_indices |
27| |
28+---------------+
29| dk_entries |
30| |
31+---------------+
32
33dk_indices is actual hashtable. It holds index in entries, or DKIX_EMPTY(-1)
34or DKIX_DUMMY(-2).
35Size of indices is dk_size. Type of each index in indices is vary on dk_size:
36
37* int8 for dk_size <= 128
38* int16 for 256 <= dk_size <= 2**15
39* int32 for 2**16 <= dk_size <= 2**31
40* int64 for 2**32 <= dk_size
41
42dk_entries is array of PyDictKeyEntry. It's size is USABLE_FRACTION(dk_size).
43DK_ENTRIES(dk) can be used to get pointer to entries.
44
45NOTE: Since negative value is used for DKIX_EMPTY and DKIX_DUMMY, type of
46dk_indices entry is signed integer and int16 is used for table which
47dk_size == 256.
48*/
49
50
51/*
52The DictObject can be in one of two forms.
53
54Either:
55 A combined table:
56 ma_values == NULL, dk_refcnt == 1.
57 Values are stored in the me_value field of the PyDictKeysObject.
58Or:
59 A split table:
60 ma_values != NULL, dk_refcnt >= 1
61 Values are stored in the ma_values array.
62 Only string (unicode) keys are allowed.
63 All dicts sharing same key must have same insertion order.
64
65There are four kinds of slots in the table (slot is index, and
66DK_ENTRIES(keys)[index] if index >= 0):
67
681. Unused. index == DKIX_EMPTY
69 Does not hold an active (key, value) pair now and never did. Unused can
70 transition to Active upon key insertion. This is each slot's initial state.
71
722. Active. index >= 0, me_key != NULL and me_value != NULL
73 Holds an active (key, value) pair. Active can transition to Dummy or
74 Pending upon key deletion (for combined and split tables respectively).
75 This is the only case in which me_value != NULL.
76
773. Dummy. index == DKIX_DUMMY (combined only)
78 Previously held an active (key, value) pair, but that was deleted and an
79 active pair has not yet overwritten the slot. Dummy can transition to
80 Active upon key insertion. Dummy slots cannot be made Unused again
81 else the probe sequence in case of collision would have no way to know
82 they were once active.
83
844. Pending. index >= 0, key != NULL, and value == NULL (split only)
85 Not yet inserted in split-table.
86*/
87
88/*
89Preserving insertion order
90
91It's simple for combined table. Since dk_entries is mostly append only, we can
92get insertion order by just iterating dk_entries.
93
94One exception is .popitem(). It removes last item in dk_entries and decrement
95dk_nentries to achieve amortized O(1). Since there are DKIX_DUMMY remains in
96dk_indices, we can't increment dk_usable even though dk_nentries is
97decremented.
98
99In split table, inserting into pending entry is allowed only for dk_entries[ix]
100where ix == mp->ma_used. Inserting into other index and deleting item cause
101converting the dict to the combined table.
102*/
103
104/* PyDict_MINSIZE is the starting size for any new dict.
105 * 8 allows dicts with no more than 5 active entries; experiments suggested
106 * this suffices for the majority of dicts (consisting mostly of usually-small
107 * dicts created to pass keyword arguments).
108 * Making this 8, rather than 4 reduces the number of resizes for most
109 * dictionaries, without any significant extra memory use.
110 */
111#define PyDict_MINSIZE 8
112

123/*
124To ensure the lookup algorithm terminates, there must be at least one Unused
125slot (NULL key) in the table.
126To avoid slowing down lookups on a near-full table, we resize the table when
127it's USABLE_FRACTION (currently two-thirds) full.
128*/
129
130#define PERTURB_SHIFT 5
131
132/*
133Major subtleties ahead: Most hash schemes depend on having a "good" hash
134function, in the sense of simulating randomness. Python doesn't: its most
135important hash functions (for ints) are very regular in common
136cases:
137
138 >>>[hash(i) for i in range(4)]
139 [0, 1, 2, 3]
140
141This isn't necessarily bad! To the contrary, in a table of size 2**i, taking
142the low-order i bits as the initial table index is extremely fast, and there
143are no collisions at all for dicts indexed by a contiguous range of ints. So
144this gives better-than-random behavior in common cases, and that's very
145desirable.
146
147OTOH, when collisions occur, the tendency to fill contiguous slices of the
148hash table makes a good collision resolution strategy crucial. Taking only
149the last i bits of the hash code is also vulnerable: for example, consider
150the list [i << 16 for i in range(20000)] as a set of keys. Since ints are
151their own hash codes, and this fits in a dict of size 2**15, the last 15 bits
152 of every hash code are all 0: they *all* map to the same table index.
153
154But catering to unusual cases should not slow the usual ones, so we just take
155the last i bits anyway. It's up to collision resolution to do the rest. If
156we *usually* find the key we're looking for on the first try (and, it turns
157out, we usually do -- the table load factor is kept under 2/3, so the odds
158are solidly in our favor), then it makes best sense to keep the initial index
159computation dirt cheap.
160
161The first half of collision resolution is to visit table indices via this
162recurrence:
163
164 j = ((5*j) + 1) mod 2**i
165
166For any initial j in range(2**i), repeating that 2**i times generates each
167int in range(2**i) exactly once (see any text on random-number generation for
168proof). By itself, this doesn't help much: like linear probing (setting
169j += 1, or j -= 1, on each loop trip), it scans the table entries in a fixed
170order. This would be bad, except that's not the only thing we do, and it's
171actually *good* in the common cases where hash keys are consecutive. In an
172example that's really too small to make this entirely clear, for a table of
173size 2**3 the order of indices is:
174
175 0 -> 1 -> 6 -> 7 -> 4 -> 5 -> 2 -> 3 -> 0 [and here it's repeating]
176
177If two things come in at index 5, the first place we look after is index 2,
178not 6, so if another comes in at index 6 the collision at 5 didn't hurt it.
179Linear probing is deadly in this case because there the fixed probe order
180is the *same* as the order consecutive keys are likely to arrive. But it's
181extremely unlikely hash codes will follow a 5*j+1 recurrence by accident,
182and certain that consecutive hash codes do not.
183
184The other half of the strategy is to get the other bits of the hash code
185into play. This is done by initializing a (unsigned) vrbl "perturb" to the
186full hash code, and changing the recurrence to:
187
188 perturb >>= PERTURB_SHIFT;
189 j = (5*j) + 1 + perturb;
190 use j % 2**i as the next table index;
191
192Now the probe sequence depends (eventually) on every bit in the hash code,
193and the pseudo-scrambling property of recurring on 5*j+1 is more valuable,
194because it quickly magnifies small differences in the bits that didn't affect
195the initial index. Note that because perturb is unsigned, if the recurrence
196is executed often enough perturb eventually becomes and remains 0. At that
197point (very rarely reached) the recurrence is on (just) 5*j+1 again, and
198that's certain to find an empty slot eventually (since it generates every int
199in range(2**i), and we make sure there's always at least one empty slot).
200
201Selecting a good value for PERTURB_SHIFT is a balancing act. You want it
202small so that the high bits of the hash code continue to affect the probe
203sequence across iterations; but you want it large so that in really bad cases
204the high-order hash bits have an effect on early iterations. 5 was "the
205best" in minimizing total collisions across experiments Tim Peters ran (on
206both normal and pathological cases), but 4 and 6 weren't significantly worse.
207
208Historical: Reimer Behrends contributed the idea of using a polynomial-based
209approach, using repeated multiplication by x in GF(2**n) where an irreducible
210polynomial for each table size was chosen such that x was a primitive root.
211Christian Tismer later extended that to use division by x instead, as an
212efficient way to get the high bits of the hash code into play. This scheme
213also gave excellent collision statistics, but was more expensive: two
214if-tests were required inside the loop; computing "the next" index took about
215the same number of operations but without as much potential parallelism
216(e.g., computing 5*j can go on at the same time as computing 1+perturb in the
217above, and then shifting perturb can be done while the table index is being
218masked); and the PyDictObject struct required a member to hold the table's
219polynomial. In Tim's experiments the current scheme ran faster, produced
220equally good collision statistics, needed less code & used less memory.
221
222*/
223

244/* Dictionary reuse scheme to save calls to malloc and free */
245#ifndef PyDict_MAXFREELIST
246#define PyDict_MAXFREELIST 80
247#endif
248static PyDictObject *free_list[PyDict_MAXFREELIST];
249static int numfree = 0;
250static PyDictKeysObject *keys_free_list[PyDict_MAXFREELIST];
251static int numfreekeys = 0;
252
253#include "clinic/dictobject.c.h"
254
255int
256PyDict_ClearFreeList(void)
257{
258 PyDictObject *op;
259 int ret = numfree + numfreekeys;
260 while (numfree) {
261 op = free_list[--numfree];
262 assert(PyDict_CheckExact(op));
263 PyObject_GC_Del(op);
264 }
265 while (numfreekeys) {
266 PyObject_FREE(keys_free_list[--numfreekeys]);
267 }
268 return ret;
269}

286#define DK_SIZE(dk) ((dk)->dk_size)
287#if SIZEOF_VOID_P > 4
288#define DK_IXSIZE(dk) \
289 (DK_SIZE(dk) <= 0xff ? \
290 1 : DK_SIZE(dk) <= 0xffff ? \
291 2 : DK_SIZE(dk) <= 0xffffffff ? \
292 4 : sizeof(int64_t))
293#else
294#define DK_IXSIZE(dk) \
295 (DK_SIZE(dk) <= 0xff ? \
296 1 : DK_SIZE(dk) <= 0xffff ? \
297 2 : sizeof(int32_t))
298#endif
299#define DK_ENTRIES(dk) \
300 ((PyDictKeyEntry*)(&(dk)->dk_indices.as_1[DK_SIZE(dk) * DK_IXSIZE(dk)]))
301
302#define DK_DEBUG_INCREF _Py_INC_REFTOTAL _Py_REF_DEBUG_COMMA
303#define DK_DEBUG_DECREF _Py_DEC_REFTOTAL _Py_REF_DEBUG_COMMA
304
305#define DK_INCREF(dk) (DK_DEBUG_INCREF ++(dk)->dk_refcnt)
306#define DK_DECREF(dk) if (DK_DEBUG_DECREF (--(dk)->dk_refcnt) == 0) free_keys_object(dk)
307#define DK_MASK(dk) (((dk)->dk_size)-1)
308#define IS_POWER_OF_2(x) (((x) & (x-1)) == 0)
309
310/* lookup indices. returns DKIX_EMPTY, DKIX_DUMMY, or ix >=0 */
311static inline Py_ssize_t
312dk_get_index(PyDictKeysObject *keys, Py_ssize_t i)
313{
314 Py_ssize_t s = DK_SIZE(keys);
315 Py_ssize_t ix;
316
317 if (s <= 0xff) {
318 int8_t *indices = keys->dk_indices.as_1;
319 ix = indices[i];
320 }
321 else if (s <= 0xffff) {
322 int16_t *indices = keys->dk_indices.as_2;
323 ix = indices[i];
324 }
325#if SIZEOF_VOID_P > 4
326 else if (s > 0xffffffff) {
327 int64_t *indices = keys->dk_indices.as_8;
328 ix = indices[i];
329 }
330#endif
331 else {
332 int32_t *indices = keys->dk_indices.as_4;
333 ix = indices[i];
334 }
335 assert(ix >= DKIX_DUMMY);
336 return ix;
337}
338
339/* write to indices. */
340static inline void
341dk_set_index(PyDictKeysObject *keys, Py_ssize_t i, Py_ssize_t ix)
342{
343 Py_ssize_t s = DK_SIZE(keys);
344
345 assert(ix >= DKIX_DUMMY);
346
347 if (s <= 0xff) {
348 int8_t *indices = keys->dk_indices.as_1;
349 assert(ix <= 0x7f);
350 indices[i] = (char)ix;
351 }
352 else if (s <= 0xffff) {
353 int16_t *indices = keys->dk_indices.as_2;
354 assert(ix <= 0x7fff);
355 indices[i] = (int16_t)ix;
356 }
357#if SIZEOF_VOID_P > 4
358 else if (s > 0xffffffff) {
359 int64_t *indices = keys->dk_indices.as_8;
360 indices[i] = ix;
361 }
362#endif
363 else {
364 int32_t *indices = keys->dk_indices.as_4;
365 assert(ix <= 0x7fffffff);
366 indices[i] = (int32_t)ix;
367 }
368}

371/* USABLE_FRACTION is the maximum dictionary load.
372 * Increasing this ratio makes dictionaries more dense resulting in more
373 * collisions. Decreasing it improves sparseness at the expense of spreading
374 * indices over more cache lines and at the cost of total memory consumed.
375 *
376 * USABLE_FRACTION must obey the following:
377 * (0 < USABLE_FRACTION(n) < n) for all n >= 2
378 *
379 * USABLE_FRACTION should be quick to calculate.
380 * Fractions around 1/2 to 2/3 seem to work well in practice.
381 */
382#define USABLE_FRACTION(n) (((n) << 1)/3)
383
384/* ESTIMATE_SIZE is reverse function of USABLE_FRACTION.
385 * This can be used to reserve enough size to insert n entries without
386 * resizing.
387 */
388#define ESTIMATE_SIZE(n) (((n)*3+1) >> 1)
389
390/* Alternative fraction that is otherwise close enough to 2n/3 to make
391 * little difference. 8 * 2/3 == 8 * 5/8 == 5. 16 * 2/3 == 16 * 5/8 == 10.
392 * 32 * 2/3 = 21, 32 * 5/8 = 20.
393 * Its advantage is that it is faster to compute on machines with slow division.
394 * #define USABLE_FRACTION(n) (((n) >> 1) + ((n) >> 2) - ((n) >> 3))
395 */
396
397/* GROWTH_RATE. Growth rate upon hitting maximum load.
398 * Currently set to used*2 + capacity/2.
399 * This means that dicts double in size when growing without deletions,
400 * but have more head room when the number of deletions is on a par with the
401 * number of insertions.
402 * Raising this to used*4 doubles memory consumption depending on the size of
403 * the dictionary, but results in half the number of resizes, less effort to
404 * resize.
405 * GROWTH_RATE was set to used*4 up to version 3.2.
406 * GROWTH_RATE was set to used*2 in version 3.3.0
407 */
408#define GROWTH_RATE(d) (((d)->ma_used*2)+((d)->ma_keys->dk_size>>1))
409
410#define ENSURE_ALLOWS_DELETIONS(d) \
411 if ((d)->ma_keys->dk_lookup == lookdict_unicode_nodummy) { \
412 (d)->ma_keys->dk_lookup = lookdict_unicode; \
413 }

421 lookdict_split, /* dk_lookup */
422 0, /* dk_usable (immutable) */
423 0, /* dk_nentries */
424 .dk_indices = { .as_1 = {DKIX_EMPTY, DKIX_EMPTY, DKIX_EMPTY, DKIX_EMPTY,
425 DKIX_EMPTY, DKIX_EMPTY, DKIX_EMPTY, DKIX_EMPTY}},
426};

432/* Uncomment to check the dict content in _PyDict_CheckConsistency() */
433/* #define DEBUG_PYDICT */

436#ifndef NDEBUG
437static int
438_PyDict_CheckConsistency(PyDictObject *mp)
439{
440 PyDictKeysObject *keys = mp->ma_keys;
441 int splitted = _PyDict_HasSplitTable(mp);
442 Py_ssize_t usable = USABLE_FRACTION(keys->dk_size);
443#ifdef DEBUG_PYDICT
444 PyDictKeyEntry *entries = DK_ENTRIES(keys);
445 Py_ssize_t i;
446#endif
447
448 assert(0 <= mp->ma_used && mp->ma_used <= usable);
449 assert(IS_POWER_OF_2(keys->dk_size));
450 assert(0 <= keys->dk_usable
451 && keys->dk_usable <= usable);
452 assert(0 <= keys->dk_nentries
453 && keys->dk_nentries <= usable);
454 assert(keys->dk_usable + keys->dk_nentries <= usable);
455
456 if (!splitted) {
457 /* combined table */
458 assert(keys->dk_refcnt == 1);
459 }
460
461#ifdef DEBUG_PYDICT
462 for (i=0; i < keys->dk_size; i++) {
463 Py_ssize_t ix = dk_get_index(keys, i);
464 assert(DKIX_DUMMY <= ix && ix <= usable);
465 }
466
467 for (i=0; i < usable; i++) {
468 PyDictKeyEntry *entry = &entries[i];
469 PyObject *key = entry->me_key;
470
471 if (key != NULL) {
472 if (PyUnicode_CheckExact(key)) {
473 Py_hash_t hash = ((PyASCIIObject *)key)->hash;
474 assert(hash != -1);
475 assert(entry->me_hash == hash);
476 }
477 else {
478 /* test_dict fails if PyObject_Hash() is called again */
479 assert(entry->me_hash != -1);
480 }
481 if (!splitted) {
482 assert(entry->me_value != NULL);
483 }
484 }
485
486 if (splitted) {
487 assert(entry->me_value == NULL);
488 }
489 }
490
491 if (splitted) {
492 /* splitted table */
493 for (i=0; i < mp->ma_used; i++) {
494 assert(mp->ma_values[i] != NULL);
495 }
496 }
497#endif
498
499 return 1;
500}
501#endif

504static PyDictKeysObject *new_keys_object(Py_ssize_t size)
505{
506 PyDictKeysObject *dk;
507 Py_ssize_t es, usable;
508
509 assert(size >= PyDict_MINSIZE);
510 assert(IS_POWER_OF_2(size));
511
512 usable = USABLE_FRACTION(size);
513 if (size <= 0xff) {
514 es = 1;
515 }
516 else if (size <= 0xffff) {
517 es = 2;
518 }
519#if SIZEOF_VOID_P > 4
520 else if (size <= 0xffffffff) {
521 es = 4;
522 }
523#endif
524 else {
525 es = sizeof(Py_ssize_t);
526 }
527
528 if (size == PyDict_MINSIZE && numfreekeys > 0) {
529 dk = keys_free_list[--numfreekeys];
530 }
531 else {
532 dk = PyObject_MALLOC(sizeof(PyDictKeysObject)
533 - Py_MEMBER_SIZE(PyDictKeysObject, dk_indices)
534 + es * size
535 + sizeof(PyDictKeyEntry) * usable);
536 if (dk == NULL) {
537 PyErr_NoMemory();
538 return NULL;
539 }
540 }
541 DK_DEBUG_INCREF dk->dk_refcnt = 1;
542 dk->dk_size = size;
543 dk->dk_usable = usable;
544 dk->dk_lookup = lookdict_unicode_nodummy;
545 dk->dk_nentries = 0;
546 memset(&dk->dk_indices.as_1[0], 0xff, es * size);
547 memset(DK_ENTRIES(dk), 0, sizeof(PyDictKeyEntry) * usable);
548 return dk;
549}
550
551static void
552free_keys_object(PyDictKeysObject *keys)
553{
554 PyDictKeyEntry *entries = DK_ENTRIES(keys);
555 Py_ssize_t i, n;
556 for (i = 0, n = keys->dk_nentries; i < n; i++) {
557 Py_XDECREF(entries[i].me_key);
558 Py_XDECREF(entries[i].me_value);
559 }
560 if (keys->dk_size == PyDict_MINSIZE && numfreekeys < PyDict_MAXFREELIST) {
561 keys_free_list[numfreekeys++] = keys;
562 return;
563 }
564 PyObject_FREE(keys);
565}

567#define new_values(size) PyMem_NEW(PyObject *, size)
568#define free_values(values) PyMem_FREE(values)

570/* Consumes a reference to the keys object */
571static PyObject *
572new_dict(PyDictKeysObject *keys, PyObject **values)
573{
574 PyDictObject *mp;
575 assert(keys != NULL);
576 if (numfree) {
577 mp = free_list[--numfree];
578 assert (mp != NULL);
579 assert (Py_TYPE(mp) == &PyDict_Type);
580 _Py_NewReference((PyObject *)mp);
581 }
582 else {
583 mp = PyObject_GC_New(PyDictObject, &PyDict_Type);
584 if (mp == NULL) {
585 DK_DECREF(keys);
586 free_values(values);
587 return NULL;
588 }
589 }
590 mp->ma_keys = keys;
591 mp->ma_values = values;
592 mp->ma_used = 0;
593 mp->ma_version_tag = DICT_NEXT_VERSION();
594 assert(_PyDict_CheckConsistency(mp));
595 return (PyObject *)mp;
596}
597
598/* Consumes a reference to the keys object */
599static PyObject *
600new_dict_with_shared_keys(PyDictKeysObject *keys)
601{
602 PyObject **values;
603 Py_ssize_t i, size;
604
605 size = USABLE_FRACTION(DK_SIZE(keys));
606 values = new_values(size);
607 if (values == NULL) {
608 DK_DECREF(keys);
609 return PyErr_NoMemory();
610 }
611 for (i = 0; i < size; i++) {
612 values[i] = NULL;
613 }
614 return new_dict(keys, values);
615}
616
617PyObject *
618PyDict_New(void)
619{
620 PyDictKeysObject *keys = new_keys_object(PyDict_MINSIZE);
621 if (keys == NULL)
622 return NULL;
623 return new_dict(keys, NULL);
624}

626/* Search index of hash table from offset of entry table */
627static Py_ssize_t
628lookdict_index(PyDictKeysObject *k, Py_hash_t hash, Py_ssize_t index)
629{
630 size_t mask = DK_MASK(k);
631 size_t perturb = (size_t)hash;
632 size_t i = (size_t)hash & mask;
633
634 for (;;) {
635 Py_ssize_t ix = dk_get_index(k, i);
636 if (ix == index) {
637 return i;
638 }
639 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY) {
640 return DKIX_EMPTY;
641 }
642 perturb >>= PERTURB_SHIFT;
643 i = mask & (i*5 + perturb + 1);
644 }
645 assert(0); /* NOT REACHED */
646 return DKIX_ERROR;
647}

649/*
650The basic lookup function used by all operations.
651This is based on Algorithm D from Knuth Vol. 3, Sec. 6.4.
652Open addressing is preferred over chaining since the link overhead for
653chaining would be substantial (100% with typical malloc overhead).
654
655The initial probe index is computed as hash mod the table size. Subsequent
656probe indices are computed as explained earlier.
657
658All arithmetic on hash should ignore overflow.
659
660The details in this version are due to Tim Peters, building on many past
661contributions by Reimer Behrends, Jyrki Alakuijala, Vladimir Marangozov and
662Christian Tismer.
663
664lookdict() is general-purpose, and may return DKIX_ERROR if (and only if) a
665comparison raises an exception.
666lookdict_unicode() below is specialized to string keys, comparison of which can
667never raise an exception; that function can never return DKIX_ERROR when key
668is string. Otherwise, it falls back to lookdict().
669lookdict_unicode_nodummy is further specialized for string keys that cannot be
670the <dummy> value.
671For both, when the key isn't found a DKIX_EMPTY is returned.
672*/
673static Py_ssize_t _Py_HOT_FUNCTION
674lookdict(PyDictObject *mp, PyObject *key,
675 Py_hash_t hash, PyObject **value_addr)
676{
677 size_t i, mask, perturb;
678 PyDictKeysObject *dk;
679 PyDictKeyEntry *ep0;
680
681top:
682 dk = mp->ma_keys;
683 ep0 = DK_ENTRIES(dk);
684 mask = DK_MASK(dk);
685 perturb = hash;
686 i = (size_t)hash & mask;
687
688 for (;;) {
689 Py_ssize_t ix = dk_get_index(dk, i);
690 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY) {
691 *value_addr = NULL;
692 return ix;
693 }
694 if (ix >= 0) {
695 PyDictKeyEntry *ep = &ep0[ix];
696 assert(ep->me_key != NULL);
697 if (ep->me_key == key) {
698 *value_addr = ep->me_value;
699 return ix;
700 }
701 if (ep->me_hash == hash) {
702 PyObject *startkey = ep->me_key;
703 Py_INCREF(startkey);
704 int cmp = PyObject_RichCompareBool(startkey, key, Py_EQ);
705 Py_DECREF(startkey);
706 if (cmp < 0) {
707 *value_addr = NULL;
708 return DKIX_ERROR;
709 }
710 if (dk == mp->ma_keys && ep->me_key == startkey) {
711 if (cmp > 0) {
712 *value_addr = ep->me_value;
713 return ix;
714 }
715 }
716 else {
717 /* The dict was mutated, restart */
718 goto top;
719 }
720 }
721 }
722 perturb >>= PERTURB_SHIFT;
723 i = (i*5 + perturb + 1) & mask;
724 }
725 assert(0); /* NOT REACHED */
726 return 0;
727}
728
729/* Specialized version for string-only keys */
730static Py_ssize_t _Py_HOT_FUNCTION
731lookdict_unicode(PyDictObject *mp, PyObject *key,
732 Py_hash_t hash, PyObject **value_addr)
733{
734 assert(mp->ma_values == NULL);
735 /* Make sure this function doesn't have to handle non-unicode keys,
736 including subclasses of str; e.g., one reason to subclass
737 unicodes is to override __eq__, and for speed we don't cater to
738 that here. */
739 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key)) {
740 mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup = lookdict;
741 return lookdict(mp, key, hash, value_addr);
742 }
743
744 PyDictKeyEntry *ep0 = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
745 size_t mask = DK_MASK(mp->ma_keys);
746 size_t perturb = (size_t)hash;
747 size_t i = (size_t)hash & mask;
748
749 for (;;) {
750 Py_ssize_t ix = dk_get_index(mp->ma_keys, i);
751 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY) {
752 *value_addr = NULL;
753 return DKIX_EMPTY;
754 }
755 if (ix >= 0) {
756 PyDictKeyEntry *ep = &ep0[ix];
757 assert(ep->me_key != NULL);
758 assert(PyUnicode_CheckExact(ep->me_key));
759 if (ep->me_key == key ||
760 (ep->me_hash == hash && unicode_eq(ep->me_key, key))) {
761 *value_addr = ep->me_value;
762 return ix;
763 }
764 }
765 perturb >>= PERTURB_SHIFT;
766 i = mask & (i*5 + perturb + 1);
767 }
768
769 assert(0); /* NOT REACHED */
770 return 0;
771}

773/* Faster version of lookdict_unicode when it is known that no <dummy> keys
774 * will be present. */
775static Py_ssize_t _Py_HOT_FUNCTION
776lookdict_unicode_nodummy(PyDictObject *mp, PyObject *key,
777 Py_hash_t hash, PyObject **value_addr)
778{
779 assert(mp->ma_values == NULL);
780 /* Make sure this function doesn't have to handle non-unicode keys,
781 including subclasses of str; e.g., one reason to subclass
782 unicodes is to override __eq__, and for speed we don't cater to
783 that here. */
784 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key)) {
785 mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup = lookdict;
786 return lookdict(mp, key, hash, value_addr);
787 }
788
789 PyDictKeyEntry *ep0 = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
790 size_t mask = DK_MASK(mp->ma_keys);
791 size_t perturb = (size_t)hash;
792 size_t i = (size_t)hash & mask;
793
794 for (;;) {
795 Py_ssize_t ix = dk_get_index(mp->ma_keys, i);
796 assert (ix != DKIX_DUMMY);
797 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY) {
798 *value_addr = NULL;
799 return DKIX_EMPTY;
800 }
801 PyDictKeyEntry *ep = &ep0[ix];
802 assert(ep->me_key != NULL);
803 assert(PyUnicode_CheckExact(ep->me_key));
804 if (ep->me_key == key ||
805 (ep->me_hash == hash && unicode_eq(ep->me_key, key))) {
806 *value_addr = ep->me_value;
807 return ix;
808 }
809 perturb >>= PERTURB_SHIFT;
810 i = mask & (i*5 + perturb + 1);
811 }
812 assert(0); /* NOT REACHED */
813 return 0;

816/* Version of lookdict for split tables.
817 * All split tables and only split tables use this lookup function.
818 * Split tables only contain unicode keys and no dummy keys,
819 * so algorithm is the same as lookdict_unicode_nodummy.
820 */
821static Py_ssize_t _Py_HOT_FUNCTION
822lookdict_split(PyDictObject *mp, PyObject *key,
823 Py_hash_t hash, PyObject **value_addr)
824{
825 /* mp must split table */
826 assert(mp->ma_values != NULL);
827 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key)) {
828 Py_ssize_t ix = lookdict(mp, key, hash, value_addr);
829 if (ix >= 0) {
830 *value_addr = mp->ma_values[ix];
831 }
832 return ix;
833 }
834
835 PyDictKeyEntry *ep0 = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
836 size_t mask = DK_MASK(mp->ma_keys);
837 size_t perturb = (size_t)hash;
838 size_t i = (size_t)hash & mask;
839
840 for (;;) {
841 Py_ssize_t ix = dk_get_index(mp->ma_keys, i);
842 assert (ix != DKIX_DUMMY);
843 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY) {
844 *value_addr = NULL;
845 return DKIX_EMPTY;
846 }
847 PyDictKeyEntry *ep = &ep0[ix];
848 assert(ep->me_key != NULL);
849 assert(PyUnicode_CheckExact(ep->me_key));
850 if (ep->me_key == key ||
851 (ep->me_hash == hash && unicode_eq(ep->me_key, key))) {
852 *value_addr = mp->ma_values[ix];
853 return ix;
854 }
855 perturb >>= PERTURB_SHIFT;
856 i = mask & (i*5 + perturb + 1);
857 }
858 assert(0); /* NOT REACHED */
859 return 0;
860}

862int
863_PyDict_HasOnlyStringKeys(PyObject *dict)
864{
865 Py_ssize_t pos = 0;
866 PyObject *key, *value;
867 assert(PyDict_Check(dict));
868 /* Shortcut */
869 if (((PyDictObject *)dict)->ma_keys->dk_lookup != lookdict)
870 return 1;
871 while (PyDict_Next(dict, &pos, &key, &value))
872 if (!PyUnicode_Check(key))
873 return 0;
874 return 1;
875}
876
877#define MAINTAIN_TRACKING(mp, key, value) \
878 do { \
879 if (!_PyObject_GC_IS_TRACKED(mp)) { \
880 if (_PyObject_GC_MAY_BE_TRACKED(key) || \
881 _PyObject_GC_MAY_BE_TRACKED(value)) { \
882 _PyObject_GC_TRACK(mp); \
883 } \
884 } \
885 } while(0)
886
887void
888_PyDict_MaybeUntrack(PyObject *op)
889{
890 PyDictObject *mp;
891 PyObject *value;
892 Py_ssize_t i, numentries;
893 PyDictKeyEntry *ep0;
894
895 if (!PyDict_CheckExact(op) || !_PyObject_GC_IS_TRACKED(op))
896 return;
897
898 mp = (PyDictObject *) op;
899 ep0 = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
900 numentries = mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries;
901 if (_PyDict_HasSplitTable(mp)) {
902 for (i = 0; i < numentries; i++) {
903 if ((value = mp->ma_values[i]) == NULL)
904 continue;
905 if (_PyObject_GC_MAY_BE_TRACKED(value)) {
906 assert(!_PyObject_GC_MAY_BE_TRACKED(ep0[i].me_key));
907 return;
908 }
909 }
910 }
911 else {
912 for (i = 0; i < numentries; i++) {
913 if ((value = ep0[i].me_value) == NULL)
914 continue;
915 if (_PyObject_GC_MAY_BE_TRACKED(value) ||
916 _PyObject_GC_MAY_BE_TRACKED(ep0[i].me_key))
917 return;
918 }
919 }
920 _PyObject_GC_UNTRACK(op);
921}

923/* Internal function to find slot for an item from its hash
924 when it is known that the key is not present in the dict.
925
926 The dict must be combined. */
927static Py_ssize_t
928find_empty_slot(PyDictKeysObject *keys, Py_hash_t hash)
929{
930 assert(keys != NULL);
931
932 const size_t mask = DK_MASK(keys);
933 size_t i = hash & mask;
934 Py_ssize_t ix = dk_get_index(keys, i);
935 for (size_t perturb = hash; ix >= 0;) {
936 perturb >>= PERTURB_SHIFT;
937 i = (i*5 + perturb + 1) & mask;
938 ix = dk_get_index(keys, i);
939 }
940 return i;
941}
942
943static int
944insertion_resize(PyDictObject *mp)
945{
946 return dictresize(mp, GROWTH_RATE(mp));
947}
948
949/*
950Internal routine to insert a new item into the table.
951Used both by the internal resize routine and by the public insert routine.
952Returns -1 if an error occurred, or 0 on success.
953*/
954static int
955insertdict(PyDictObject *mp, PyObject *key, Py_hash_t hash, PyObject *value)
956{
957 PyObject *old_value;
958 PyDictKeyEntry *ep;
959
960 Py_INCREF(key);
961 Py_INCREF(value);
962 if (mp->ma_values != NULL && !PyUnicode_CheckExact(key)) {
963 if (insertion_resize(mp) < 0)
964 goto Fail;
965 }
966
967 Py_ssize_t ix = mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup(mp, key, hash, &old_value);
968 if (ix == DKIX_ERROR)
969 goto Fail;
970
971 assert(PyUnicode_CheckExact(key) || mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup == lookdict);
972 MAINTAIN_TRACKING(mp, key, value);
973
974 /* When insertion order is different from shared key, we can't share
975 * the key anymore. Convert this instance to combine table.
976 */
977 if (_PyDict_HasSplitTable(mp) &&
978 ((ix >= 0 && old_value == NULL && mp->ma_used != ix) ||
979 (ix == DKIX_EMPTY && mp->ma_used != mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries))) {
980 if (insertion_resize(mp) < 0)
981 goto Fail;
982 ix = DKIX_EMPTY;
983 }
984
985 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY) {
986 /* Insert into new slot. */
987 assert(old_value == NULL);
988 if (mp->ma_keys->dk_usable <= 0) {
989 /* Need to resize. */
990 if (insertion_resize(mp) < 0)
991 goto Fail;
992 }
993 Py_ssize_t hashpos = find_empty_slot(mp->ma_keys, hash);
994 ep = &DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys)[mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries];
995 dk_set_index(mp->ma_keys, hashpos, mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries);
996 ep->me_key = key;
997 ep->me_hash = hash;
998 if (mp->ma_values) {
999 assert (mp->ma_values[mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries] == NULL);
1000 mp->ma_values[mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries] = value;
1001 }
1002 else {
1003 ep->me_value = value;
1004 }
1005 mp->ma_used++;
1006 mp->ma_version_tag = DICT_NEXT_VERSION();
1007 mp->ma_keys->dk_usable--;
1008 mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries++;
1009 assert(mp->ma_keys->dk_usable >= 0);
1010 assert(_PyDict_CheckConsistency(mp));
1011 return 0;
1012 }
1013
1014 if (_PyDict_HasSplitTable(mp)) {
1015 mp->ma_values[ix] = value;
1016 if (old_value == NULL) {
1017 /* pending state */
1018 assert(ix == mp->ma_used);
1019 mp->ma_used++;
1020 }
1021 }
1022 else {
1023 assert(old_value != NULL);
1024 DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys)[ix].me_value = value;
1025 }
1026
1027 mp->ma_version_tag = DICT_NEXT_VERSION();
1028 Py_XDECREF(old_value); /* which **CAN** re-enter (see issue #22653) */
1029 assert(_PyDict_CheckConsistency(mp));
1030 Py_DECREF(key);
1031 return 0;
1032
1033Fail:
1034 Py_DECREF(value);
1035 Py_DECREF(key);
1036 return -1;
1037}
1038
1039/*
1040Internal routine used by dictresize() to buid a hashtable of entries.
1041*/
1042static void
1043build_indices(PyDictKeysObject *keys, PyDictKeyEntry *ep, Py_ssize_t n)
1044{
1045 size_t mask = (size_t)DK_SIZE(keys) - 1;
1046 for (Py_ssize_t ix = 0; ix != n; ix++, ep++) {
1047 Py_hash_t hash = ep->me_hash;
1048 size_t i = hash & mask;
1049 for (size_t perturb = hash; dk_get_index(keys, i) != DKIX_EMPTY;) {
1050 perturb >>= PERTURB_SHIFT;
1051 i = mask & (i*5 + perturb + 1);
1052 }
1053 dk_set_index(keys, i, ix);
1054 }
1055}
1056
1057/*
1058Restructure the table by allocating a new table and reinserting all
1059items again. When entries have been deleted, the new table may
1060actually be smaller than the old one.
1061If a table is split (its keys and hashes are shared, its values are not),
1062then the values are temporarily copied into the table, it is resized as
1063a combined table, then the me_value slots in the old table are NULLed out.
1064After resizing a table is always combined,
1065but can be resplit by make_keys_shared().
1066*/
1067static int
1068dictresize(PyDictObject *mp, Py_ssize_t minsize)
1069{
1070 Py_ssize_t newsize, numentries;
1071 PyDictKeysObject *oldkeys;
1072 PyObject **oldvalues;
1073 PyDictKeyEntry *oldentries, *newentries;
1074
1075 /* Find the smallest table size > minused. */
1076 for (newsize = PyDict_MINSIZE;
1077 newsize < minsize && newsize > 0;
1078 newsize <<= 1)
1079 ;
1080 if (newsize <= 0) {
1081 PyErr_NoMemory();
1082 return -1;
1083 }
1084
1085 oldkeys = mp->ma_keys;
1086
1087 /* NOTE: Current odict checks mp->ma_keys to detect resize happen.
1088 * So we can't reuse oldkeys even if oldkeys->dk_size == newsize.
1089 * TODO: Try reusing oldkeys when reimplement odict.
1090 */
1091
1092 /* Allocate a new table. */
1093 mp->ma_keys = new_keys_object(newsize);
1094 if (mp->ma_keys == NULL) {
1095 mp->ma_keys = oldkeys;
1096 return -1;
1097 }
1098 // New table must be large enough.
1099 assert(mp->ma_keys->dk_usable >= mp->ma_used);
1100 if (oldkeys->dk_lookup == lookdict)
1101 mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup = lookdict;
1102
1103 numentries = mp->ma_used;
1104 oldentries = DK_ENTRIES(oldkeys);
1105 newentries = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
1106 oldvalues = mp->ma_values;
1107 if (oldvalues != NULL) {
1108 /* Convert split table into new combined table.
1109 * We must incref keys; we can transfer values.
1110 * Note that values of split table is always dense.
1111 */
1112 for (Py_ssize_t i = 0; i < numentries; i++) {
1113 assert(oldvalues[i] != NULL);
1114 PyDictKeyEntry *ep = &oldentries[i];
1115 PyObject *key = ep->me_key;
1116 Py_INCREF(key);
1117 newentries[i].me_key = key;
1118 newentries[i].me_hash = ep->me_hash;
1119 newentries[i].me_value = oldvalues[i];
1120 }
1121
1122 DK_DECREF(oldkeys);
1123 mp->ma_values = NULL;
1124 if (oldvalues != empty_values) {
1125 free_values(oldvalues);
1126 }
1127 }
1128 else { // combined table.
1129 if (oldkeys->dk_nentries == numentries) {
1130 memcpy(newentries, oldentries, numentries * sizeof(PyDictKeyEntry));
1131 }
1132 else {
1133 PyDictKeyEntry *ep = oldentries;
1134 for (Py_ssize_t i = 0; i < numentries; i++) {
1135 while (ep->me_value == NULL)
1136 ep++;
1137 newentries[i] = *ep++;
1138 }
1139 }
1140
1141 assert(oldkeys->dk_lookup != lookdict_split);
1142 assert(oldkeys->dk_refcnt == 1);
1143 if (oldkeys->dk_size == PyDict_MINSIZE &&
1144 numfreekeys < PyDict_MAXFREELIST) {
1145 DK_DEBUG_DECREF keys_free_list[numfreekeys++] = oldkeys;
1146 }
1147 else {
1148 DK_DEBUG_DECREF PyObject_FREE(oldkeys);
1149 }
1150 }
1151
1152 build_indices(mp->ma_keys, newentries, numentries);
1153 mp->ma_keys->dk_usable -= numentries;
1154 mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries = numentries;
1155 return 0;
1156}
1157
1158/* Returns NULL if unable to split table.
1159 * A NULL return does not necessarily indicate an error */
1160static PyDictKeysObject *
1161make_keys_shared(PyObject *op)
1162{
1163 Py_ssize_t i;
1164 Py_ssize_t size;
1165 PyDictObject *mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
1166
1167 if (!PyDict_CheckExact(op))
1168 return NULL;
1169 if (!_PyDict_HasSplitTable(mp)) {
1170 PyDictKeyEntry *ep0;
1171 PyObject **values;
1172 assert(mp->ma_keys->dk_refcnt == 1);
1173 if (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup == lookdict) {
1174 return NULL;
1175 }
1176 else if (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup == lookdict_unicode) {
1177 /* Remove dummy keys */
1178 if (dictresize(mp, DK_SIZE(mp->ma_keys)))
1179 return NULL;
1180 }
1181 assert(mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup == lookdict_unicode_nodummy);
1182 /* Copy values into a new array */
1183 ep0 = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
1184 size = USABLE_FRACTION(DK_SIZE(mp->ma_keys));
1185 values = new_values(size);
1186 if (values == NULL) {
1187 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_MemoryError,
1188 "Not enough memory to allocate new values array");
1189 return NULL;
1190 }
1191 for (i = 0; i < size; i++) {
1192 values[i] = ep0[i].me_value;
1193 ep0[i].me_value = NULL;
1194 }
1195 mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup = lookdict_split;
1196 mp->ma_values = values;
1197 }
1198 DK_INCREF(mp->ma_keys);
1199 return mp->ma_keys;
1200}
1201
1202PyObject *
1203_PyDict_NewPresized(Py_ssize_t minused)
1204{
1205 const Py_ssize_t max_presize = 128 * 1024;
1206 Py_ssize_t newsize;
1207 PyDictKeysObject *new_keys;
1208
1209 /* There are no strict guarantee that returned dict can contain minused
1210 * items without resize. So we create medium size dict instead of very
1211 * large dict or MemoryError.
1212 */
1213 if (minused > USABLE_FRACTION(max_presize)) {
1214 newsize = max_presize;
1215 }
1216 else {
1217 Py_ssize_t minsize = ESTIMATE_SIZE(minused);
1218 newsize = PyDict_MINSIZE;
1219 while (newsize < minsize) {
1220 newsize <<= 1;
1221 }
1222 }
1223 assert(IS_POWER_OF_2(newsize));
1224
1225 new_keys = new_keys_object(newsize);
1226 if (new_keys == NULL)
1227 return NULL;
1228 return new_dict(new_keys, NULL);
1229}

1231/* Note that, for historical reasons, PyDict_GetItem() suppresses all errors
1232 * that may occur (originally dicts supported only string keys, and exceptions
1233 * weren't possible). So, while the original intent was that a NULL return
1234 * meant the key wasn't present, in reality it can mean that, or that an error
1235 * (suppressed) occurred while computing the key's hash, or that some error
1236 * (suppressed) occurred when comparing keys in the dict's internal probe
1237 * sequence. A nasty example of the latter is when a Python-coded comparison
1238 * function hits a stack-depth error, which can cause this to return NULL
1239 * even if the key is present.
1240 */
1241PyObject *
1242PyDict_GetItem(PyObject *op, PyObject *key)
1243{
1244 Py_hash_t hash;
1245 Py_ssize_t ix;
1246 PyDictObject *mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
1247 PyThreadState *tstate;
1248 PyObject *value;
1249
1250 if (!PyDict_Check(op))
1251 return NULL;
1252 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key) ||
1253 (hash = ((PyASCIIObject *) key)->hash) == -1)
1254 {
1255 hash = PyObject_Hash(key);
1256 if (hash == -1) {
1257 PyErr_Clear();
1258 return NULL;
1259 }
1260 }
1261
1262 /* We can arrive here with a NULL tstate during initialization: try
1263 running "python -Wi" for an example related to string interning.
1264 Let's just hope that no exception occurs then... This must be
1265 _PyThreadState_Current and not PyThreadState_GET() because in debug
1266 mode, the latter complains if tstate is NULL. */
1267 tstate = PyThreadState_GET();
1268 if (tstate != NULL && tstate->curexc_type != NULL) {
1269 /* preserve the existing exception */
1270 PyObject *err_type, *err_value, *err_tb;
1271 PyErr_Fetch(&err_type, &err_value, &err_tb);
1272 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &value);
1273 /* ignore errors */
1274 PyErr_Restore(err_type, err_value, err_tb);
1275 if (ix < 0)
1276 return NULL;
1277 }
1278 else {
1279 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &value);
1280 if (ix < 0) {
1281 PyErr_Clear();
1282 return NULL;
1283 }
1284 }
1285 return value;
1286}
1287
1288/* Same as PyDict_GetItemWithError() but with hash supplied by caller.
1289 This returns NULL *with* an exception set if an exception occurred.
1290 It returns NULL *without* an exception set if the key wasn't present.
1291*/
1292PyObject *
1293_PyDict_GetItem_KnownHash(PyObject *op, PyObject *key, Py_hash_t hash)
1294{
1295 Py_ssize_t ix;
1296 PyDictObject *mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
1297 PyObject *value;
1298
1299 if (!PyDict_Check(op)) {
1300 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
1301 return NULL;
1302 }
1303
1304 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &value);
1305 if (ix < 0) {
1306 return NULL;
1307 }
1308 return value;
1309}
1310
1311/* Variant of PyDict_GetItem() that doesn't suppress exceptions.
1312 This returns NULL *with* an exception set if an exception occurred.
1313 It returns NULL *without* an exception set if the key wasn't present.
1314*/
1315PyObject *
1316PyDict_GetItemWithError(PyObject *op, PyObject *key)
1317{
1318 Py_ssize_t ix;
1319 Py_hash_t hash;
1320 PyDictObject*mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
1321 PyObject *value;
1322
1323 if (!PyDict_Check(op)) {
1324 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
1325 return NULL;
1326 }
1327 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key) ||
1328 (hash = ((PyASCIIObject *) key)->hash) == -1)
1329 {
1330 hash = PyObject_Hash(key);
1331 if (hash == -1) {
1332 return NULL;
1333 }
1334 }
1335
1336 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &value);
1337 if (ix < 0)
1338 return NULL;
1339 return value;
1340}

1342PyObject *
1343_PyDict_GetItemIdWithError(PyObject *dp, struct _Py_Identifier *key)
1344{
1345 PyObject *kv;
1346 kv = _PyUnicode_FromId(key); /* borrowed */
1347 if (kv == NULL)
1348 return NULL;
1349 return PyDict_GetItemWithError(dp, kv);
1350}

1352/* Fast version of global value lookup (LOAD_GLOBAL).
1353 * Lookup in globals, then builtins.
1354 *
1355 * Raise an exception and return NULL if an error occurred (ex: computing the
1356 * key hash failed, key comparison failed, ...). Return NULL if the key doesn't
1357 * exist. Return the value if the key exists.
1358 */
1359PyObject *
1360_PyDict_LoadGlobal(PyDictObject *globals, PyDictObject *builtins, PyObject *key)
1361{
1362 Py_ssize_t ix;
1363 Py_hash_t hash;
1364 PyObject *value;
1365
1366 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key) ||
1367 (hash = ((PyASCIIObject *) key)->hash) == -1)
1368 {
1369 hash = PyObject_Hash(key);
1370 if (hash == -1)
1371 return NULL;
1372 }
1373
1374 /* namespace 1: globals */
1375 ix = globals->ma_keys->dk_lookup(globals, key, hash, &value);
1376 if (ix == DKIX_ERROR)
1377 return NULL;
1378 if (ix != DKIX_EMPTY && value != NULL)
1379 return value;
1380
1381 /* namespace 2: builtins */
1382 ix = builtins->ma_keys->dk_lookup(builtins, key, hash, &value);
1383 if (ix < 0)
1384 return NULL;
1385 return value;
1386}

1388/* CAUTION: PyDict_SetItem() must guarantee that it won't resize the
1389 * dictionary if it's merely replacing the value for an existing key.
1390 * This means that it's safe to loop over a dictionary with PyDict_Next()
1391 * and occasionally replace a value -- but you can't insert new keys or
1392 * remove them.
1393 */
1394int
1395PyDict_SetItem(PyObject *op, PyObject *key, PyObject *value)
1396{
1397 PyDictObject *mp;
1398 Py_hash_t hash;
1399 if (!PyDict_Check(op)) {
1400 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
1401 return -1;
1402 }
1403 assert(key);
1404 assert(value);
1405 mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
1406 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key) ||
1407 (hash = ((PyASCIIObject *) key)->hash) == -1)
1408 {
1409 hash = PyObject_Hash(key);
1410 if (hash == -1)
1411 return -1;
1412 }
1413
1414 /* insertdict() handles any resizing that might be necessary */
1415 return insertdict(mp, key, hash, value);
1416}
1417
1418int
1419_PyDict_SetItem_KnownHash(PyObject *op, PyObject *key, PyObject *value,
1420 Py_hash_t hash)
1421{
1422 PyDictObject *mp;
1423
1424 if (!PyDict_Check(op)) {
1425 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
1426 return -1;
1427 }
1428 assert(key);
1429 assert(value);
1430 assert(hash != -1);
1431 mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
1432
1433 /* insertdict() handles any resizing that might be necessary */
1434 return insertdict(mp, key, hash, value);
1435}

1437static int
1438delitem_common(PyDictObject *mp, Py_hash_t hash, Py_ssize_t ix,
1439 PyObject *old_value)
1440{
1441 PyObject *old_key;
1442 PyDictKeyEntry *ep;
1443
1444 Py_ssize_t hashpos = lookdict_index(mp->ma_keys, hash, ix);
1445 assert(hashpos >= 0);
1446
1447 mp->ma_used--;
1448 mp->ma_version_tag = DICT_NEXT_VERSION();
1449 ep = &DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys)[ix];
1450 dk_set_index(mp->ma_keys, hashpos, DKIX_DUMMY);
1451 ENSURE_ALLOWS_DELETIONS(mp);
1452 old_key = ep->me_key;
1453 ep->me_key = NULL;
1454 ep->me_value = NULL;
1455 Py_DECREF(old_key);
1456 Py_DECREF(old_value);
1457
1458 assert(_PyDict_CheckConsistency(mp));
1459 return 0;
1460}

1462int
1463PyDict_DelItem(PyObject *op, PyObject *key)
1464{
1465 Py_hash_t hash;
1466 assert(key);
1467 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key) ||
1468 (hash = ((PyASCIIObject *) key)->hash) == -1) {
1469 hash = PyObject_Hash(key);
1470 if (hash == -1)
1471 return -1;
1472 }
1473
1474 return _PyDict_DelItem_KnownHash(op, key, hash);
1475}
1476
1477int
1478_PyDict_DelItem_KnownHash(PyObject *op, PyObject *key, Py_hash_t hash)
1479{
1480 Py_ssize_t ix;
1481 PyDictObject *mp;
1482 PyObject *old_value;
1483
1484 if (!PyDict_Check(op)) {
1485 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
1486 return -1;
1487 }
1488 assert(key);
1489 assert(hash != -1);
1490 mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
1491 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &old_value);
1492 if (ix == DKIX_ERROR)
1493 return -1;
1494 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY || old_value == NULL) {
1495 _PyErr_SetKeyError(key);
1496 return -1;
1497 }
1498
1499 // Split table doesn't allow deletion. Combine it.
1500 if (_PyDict_HasSplitTable(mp)) {
1501 if (dictresize(mp, DK_SIZE(mp->ma_keys))) {
1502 return -1;
1503 }
1504 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &old_value);
1505 assert(ix >= 0);
1506 }
1507
1508 return delitem_common(mp, hash, ix, old_value);
1509}

1511/* This function promises that the predicate -> deletion sequence is atomic
1512 * (i.e. protected by the GIL), assuming the predicate itself doesn't
1513 * release the GIL.
1514 */
1515int
1516_PyDict_DelItemIf(PyObject *op, PyObject *key,
1517 int (*predicate)(PyObject *value))
1518{
1519 Py_ssize_t hashpos, ix;
1520 PyDictObject *mp;
1521 Py_hash_t hash;
1522 PyObject *old_value;
1523 int res;
1524
1525 if (!PyDict_Check(op)) {
1526 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
1527 return -1;
1528 }
1529 assert(key);
1530 hash = PyObject_Hash(key);
1531 if (hash == -1)
1532 return -1;
1533 mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
1534 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &old_value);
1535 if (ix == DKIX_ERROR)
1536 return -1;
1537 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY || old_value == NULL) {
1538 _PyErr_SetKeyError(key);
1539 return -1;
1540 }
1541
1542 // Split table doesn't allow deletion. Combine it.
1543 if (_PyDict_HasSplitTable(mp)) {
1544 if (dictresize(mp, DK_SIZE(mp->ma_keys))) {
1545 return -1;
1546 }
1547 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &old_value);
1548 assert(ix >= 0);
1549 }
1550
1551 res = predicate(old_value);
1552 if (res == -1)
1553 return -1;
1554
1555 hashpos = lookdict_index(mp->ma_keys, hash, ix);
1556 assert(hashpos >= 0);
1557
1558 if (res > 0)
1559 return delitem_common(mp, hashpos, ix, old_value);
1560 else
1561 return 0;
1562}

1564
1565void
1566PyDict_Clear(PyObject *op)
1567{
1568 PyDictObject *mp;
1569 PyDictKeysObject *oldkeys;
1570 PyObject **oldvalues;
1571 Py_ssize_t i, n;
1572
1573 if (!PyDict_Check(op))
1574 return;
1575 mp = ((PyDictObject *)op);
1576 oldkeys = mp->ma_keys;
1577 oldvalues = mp->ma_values;
1578 if (oldvalues == empty_values)
1579 return;
1580 /* Empty the dict... */
1581 DK_INCREF(Py_EMPTY_KEYS);
1582 mp->ma_keys = Py_EMPTY_KEYS;
1583 mp->ma_values = empty_values;
1584 mp->ma_used = 0;
1585 mp->ma_version_tag = DICT_NEXT_VERSION();
1586 /* ...then clear the keys and values */
1587 if (oldvalues != NULL) {
1588 n = oldkeys->dk_nentries;
1589 for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
1590 Py_CLEAR(oldvalues[i]);
1591 free_values(oldvalues);
1592 DK_DECREF(oldkeys);
1593 }
1594 else {
1595 assert(oldkeys->dk_refcnt == 1);
1596 DK_DECREF(oldkeys);
1597 }
1598 assert(_PyDict_CheckConsistency(mp));
1599}

1601/* Internal version of PyDict_Next that returns a hash value in addition
1602 * to the key and value.
1603 * Return 1 on success, return 0 when the reached the end of the dictionary
1604 * (or if op is not a dictionary)
1605 */
1606int
1607_PyDict_Next(PyObject *op, Py_ssize_t *ppos, PyObject **pkey,
1608 PyObject **pvalue, Py_hash_t *phash)
1609{
1610 Py_ssize_t i;
1611 PyDictObject *mp;
1612 PyDictKeyEntry *entry_ptr;
1613 PyObject *value;
1614
1615 if (!PyDict_Check(op))
1616 return 0;
1617 mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
1618 i = *ppos;
1619 if (mp->ma_values) {
1620 if (i < 0 || i >= mp->ma_used)
1621 return 0;
1622 /* values of split table is always dense */
1623 entry_ptr = &DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys)[i];
1624 value = mp->ma_values[i];
1625 assert(value != NULL);
1626 }
1627 else {
1628 Py_ssize_t n = mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries;
1629 if (i < 0 || i >= n)
1630 return 0;
1631 entry_ptr = &DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys)[i];
1632 while (i < n && entry_ptr->me_value == NULL) {
1633 entry_ptr++;
1634 i++;
1635 }
1636 if (i >= n)
1637 return 0;
1638 value = entry_ptr->me_value;
1639 }
1640 *ppos = i+1;
1641 if (pkey)
1642 *pkey = entry_ptr->me_key;
1643 if (phash)
1644 *phash = entry_ptr->me_hash;
1645 if (pvalue)
1646 *pvalue = value;
1647 return 1;
1648}
1649
1650/*
1651 * Iterate over a dict. Use like so:
1652 *
1653 * Py_ssize_t i;
1654 * PyObject *key, *value;
1655 * i = 0; # important! i should not otherwise be changed by you
1656 * while (PyDict_Next(yourdict, &i, &key, &value)) {
1657 * Refer to borrowed references in key and value.
1658 * }
1659 *
1660 * Return 1 on success, return 0 when the reached the end of the dictionary
1661 * (or if op is not a dictionary)
1662 *
1663 * CAUTION: In general, it isn't safe to use PyDict_Next in a loop that
1664 * mutates the dict. One exception: it is safe if the loop merely changes
1665 * the values associated with the keys (but doesn't insert new keys or
1666 * delete keys), via PyDict_SetItem().
1667 */
1668int
1669PyDict_Next(PyObject *op, Py_ssize_t *ppos, PyObject **pkey, PyObject **pvalue)
1670{
1671 return _PyDict_Next(op, ppos, pkey, pvalue, NULL);
1672}
1673
1674/* Internal version of dict.pop(). */
1675PyObject *
1676_PyDict_Pop_KnownHash(PyObject *dict, PyObject *key, Py_hash_t hash, PyObject *deflt)
1677{
1678 Py_ssize_t ix, hashpos;
1679 PyObject *old_value, *old_key;
1680 PyDictKeyEntry *ep;
1681 PyDictObject *mp;
1682
1683 assert(PyDict_Check(dict));
1684 mp = (PyDictObject *)dict;
1685
1686 if (mp->ma_used == 0) {
1687 if (deflt) {
1688 Py_INCREF(deflt);
1689 return deflt;
1690 }
1691 _PyErr_SetKeyError(key);
1692 return NULL;
1693 }
1694 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &old_value);
1695 if (ix == DKIX_ERROR)
1696 return NULL;
1697 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY || old_value == NULL) {
1698 if (deflt) {
1699 Py_INCREF(deflt);
1700 return deflt;
1701 }
1702 _PyErr_SetKeyError(key);
1703 return NULL;
1704 }
1705
1706 // Split table doesn't allow deletion. Combine it.
1707 if (_PyDict_HasSplitTable(mp)) {
1708 if (dictresize(mp, DK_SIZE(mp->ma_keys))) {
1709 return NULL;
1710 }
1711 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &old_value);
1712 assert(ix >= 0);
1713 }
1714
1715 hashpos = lookdict_index(mp->ma_keys, hash, ix);
1716 assert(hashpos >= 0);
1717 assert(old_value != NULL);
1718 mp->ma_used--;
1719 mp->ma_version_tag = DICT_NEXT_VERSION();
1720 dk_set_index(mp->ma_keys, hashpos, DKIX_DUMMY);
1721 ep = &DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys)[ix];
1722 ENSURE_ALLOWS_DELETIONS(mp);
1723 old_key = ep->me_key;
1724 ep->me_key = NULL;
1725 ep->me_value = NULL;
1726 Py_DECREF(old_key);
1727
1728 assert(_PyDict_CheckConsistency(mp));
1729 return old_value;
1730}
1731
1732PyObject *
1733_PyDict_Pop(PyObject *dict, PyObject *key, PyObject *deflt)
1734{
1735 Py_hash_t hash;
1736
1737 if (((PyDictObject *)dict)->ma_used == 0) {
1738 if (deflt) {
1739 Py_INCREF(deflt);
1740 return deflt;
1741 }
1742 _PyErr_SetKeyError(key);
1743 return NULL;
1744 }
1745 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key) ||
1746 (hash = ((PyASCIIObject *) key)->hash) == -1) {
1747 hash = PyObject_Hash(key);
1748 if (hash == -1)
1749 return NULL;
1750 }
1751 return _PyDict_Pop_KnownHash(dict, key, hash, deflt);
1752}

1754/* Internal version of dict.from_keys(). It is subclass-friendly. */
1755PyObject *
1756_PyDict_FromKeys(PyObject *cls, PyObject *iterable, PyObject *value)
1757{
1758 PyObject *it; /* iter(iterable) */
1759 PyObject *key;
1760 PyObject *d;
1761 int status;
1762
1763 d = _PyObject_CallNoArg(cls);
1764 if (d == NULL)
1765 return NULL;
1766
1767 if (PyDict_CheckExact(d) && ((PyDictObject *)d)->ma_used == 0) {
1768 if (PyDict_CheckExact(iterable)) {
1769 PyDictObject *mp = (PyDictObject *)d;
1770 PyObject *oldvalue;
1771 Py_ssize_t pos = 0;
1772 PyObject *key;
1773 Py_hash_t hash;
1774
1775 if (dictresize(mp, ESTIMATE_SIZE(PyDict_GET_SIZE(iterable)))) {
1776 Py_DECREF(d);
1777 return NULL;
1778 }
1779
1780 while (_PyDict_Next(iterable, &pos, &key, &oldvalue, &hash)) {
1781 if (insertdict(mp, key, hash, value)) {
1782 Py_DECREF(d);
1783 return NULL;
1784 }
1785 }
1786 return d;
1787 }
1788 if (PyAnySet_CheckExact(iterable)) {
1789 PyDictObject *mp = (PyDictObject *)d;
1790 Py_ssize_t pos = 0;
1791 PyObject *key;
1792 Py_hash_t hash;
1793
1794 if (dictresize(mp, ESTIMATE_SIZE(PySet_GET_SIZE(iterable)))) {
1795 Py_DECREF(d);
1796 return NULL;
1797 }
1798
1799 while (_PySet_NextEntry(iterable, &pos, &key, &hash)) {
1800 if (insertdict(mp, key, hash, value)) {
1801 Py_DECREF(d);
1802 return NULL;
1803 }
1804 }
1805 return d;
1806 }
1807 }
1808
1809 it = PyObject_GetIter(iterable);
1810 if (it == NULL){
1811 Py_DECREF(d);
1812 return NULL;
1813 }
1814
1815 if (PyDict_CheckExact(d)) {
1816 while ((key = PyIter_Next(it)) != NULL) {
1817 status = PyDict_SetItem(d, key, value);
1818 Py_DECREF(key);
1819 if (status < 0)
1820 goto Fail;
1821 }
1822 } else {
1823 while ((key = PyIter_Next(it)) != NULL) {
1824 status = PyObject_SetItem(d, key, value);
1825 Py_DECREF(key);
1826 if (status < 0)
1827 goto Fail;
1828 }
1829 }
1830
1831 if (PyErr_Occurred())
1832 goto Fail;
1833 Py_DECREF(it);
1834 return d;
1835
1836Fail:
1837 Py_DECREF(it);
1838 Py_DECREF(d);
1839 return NULL;
1840}

1843
1844static void
1845dict_dealloc(PyDictObject *mp)
1846{
1847 PyObject **values = mp->ma_values;
1848 PyDictKeysObject *keys = mp->ma_keys;
1849 Py_ssize_t i, n;
1850
1851 /* bpo-31095: UnTrack is needed before calling any callbacks */
1852 PyObject_GC_UnTrack(mp);
1853 Py_TRASHCAN_SAFE_BEGIN(mp)
1854 if (values != NULL) {
1855 if (values != empty_values) {
1856 for (i = 0, n = mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries; i < n; i++) {
1857 Py_XDECREF(values[i]);
1858 }
1859 free_values(values);
1860 }
1861 DK_DECREF(keys);
1862 }
1863 else if (keys != NULL) {
1864 assert(keys->dk_refcnt == 1);
1865 DK_DECREF(keys);
1866 }
1867 if (numfree < PyDict_MAXFREELIST && Py_TYPE(mp) == &PyDict_Type)
1868 free_list[numfree++] = mp;
1869 else
1870 Py_TYPE(mp)->tp_free((PyObject *)mp);
1871 Py_TRASHCAN_SAFE_END(mp)
1872}

1874
1875static PyObject *
1876dict_repr(PyDictObject *mp)
1877{
1878 Py_ssize_t i;
1879 PyObject *key = NULL, *value = NULL;
1880 _PyUnicodeWriter writer;
1881 int first;
1882
1883 i = Py_ReprEnter((PyObject *)mp);
1884 if (i != 0) {
1885 return i > 0 ? PyUnicode_FromString("{...}") : NULL;
1886 }
1887
1888 if (mp->ma_used == 0) {
1889 Py_ReprLeave((PyObject *)mp);
1890 return PyUnicode_FromString("{}");
1891 }
1892
1893 _PyUnicodeWriter_Init(&writer);
1894 writer.overallocate = 1;
1895 /* "{" + "1: 2" + ", 3: 4" * (len - 1) + "}" */
1896 writer.min_length = 1 + 4 + (2 + 4) * (mp->ma_used - 1) + 1;
1897
1898 if (_PyUnicodeWriter_WriteChar(&writer, '{') < 0)
1899 goto error;
1900
1901 /* Do repr() on each key+value pair, and insert ": " between them.
1902 Note that repr may mutate the dict. */
1903 i = 0;
1904 first = 1;
1905 while (PyDict_Next((PyObject *)mp, &i, &key, &value)) {
1906 PyObject *s;
1907 int res;
1908
1909 /* Prevent repr from deleting key or value during key format. */
1910 Py_INCREF(key);
1911 Py_INCREF(value);
1912
1913 if (!first) {
1914 if (_PyUnicodeWriter_WriteASCIIString(&writer, ", ", 2) < 0)
1915 goto error;
1916 }
1917 first = 0;
1918
1919 s = PyObject_Repr(key);
1920 if (s == NULL)
1921 goto error;
1922 res = _PyUnicodeWriter_WriteStr(&writer, s);
1923 Py_DECREF(s);
1924 if (res < 0)
1925 goto error;
1926
1927 if (_PyUnicodeWriter_WriteASCIIString(&writer, ": ", 2) < 0)
1928 goto error;
1929
1930 s = PyObject_Repr(value);
1931 if (s == NULL)
1932 goto error;
1933 res = _PyUnicodeWriter_WriteStr(&writer, s);
1934 Py_DECREF(s);
1935 if (res < 0)
1936 goto error;
1937
1938 Py_CLEAR(key);
1939 Py_CLEAR(value);
1940 }
1941
1942 writer.overallocate = 0;
1943 if (_PyUnicodeWriter_WriteChar(&writer, '}') < 0)
1944 goto error;
1945
1946 Py_ReprLeave((PyObject *)mp);
1947
1948 return _PyUnicodeWriter_Finish(&writer);
1949
1950error:
1951 Py_ReprLeave((PyObject *)mp);
1952 _PyUnicodeWriter_Dealloc(&writer);
1953 Py_XDECREF(key);
1954 Py_XDECREF(value);
1955 return NULL;
1956}

1964static PyObject *
1965dict_subscript(PyDictObject *mp, PyObject *key)
1966{
1967 Py_ssize_t ix;
1968 Py_hash_t hash;
1969 PyObject *value;
1970
1971 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key) ||
1972 (hash = ((PyASCIIObject *) key)->hash) == -1) {
1973 hash = PyObject_Hash(key);
1974 if (hash == -1)
1975 return NULL;
1976 }
1977 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &value);
1978 if (ix == DKIX_ERROR)
1979 return NULL;
1980 if (ix == DKIX_EMPTY || value == NULL) {
1981 if (!PyDict_CheckExact(mp)) {
1982 /* Look up __missing__ method if we're a subclass. */
1983 PyObject *missing, *res;
1984 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__missing__);
1985 missing = _PyObject_LookupSpecial((PyObject *)mp, &PyId___missing__);
1986 if (missing != NULL) {
1987 res = PyObject_CallFunctionObjArgs(missing,
1988 key, NULL);
1989 Py_DECREF(missing);
1990 return res;
1991 }
1992 else if (PyErr_Occurred())
1993 return NULL;
1994 }
1995 _PyErr_SetKeyError(key);
1996 return NULL;
1997 }
1998 Py_INCREF(value);
1999 return value;
2000}

2003dict_ass_sub(PyDictObject *mp, PyObject *v, PyObject *w)
2004{
2005 if (w == NULL)
2006 return PyDict_DelItem((PyObject *)mp, v);
2007 else
2008 return PyDict_SetItem((PyObject *)mp, v, w);
2009}

2016
2017static PyObject *
2018dict_keys(PyDictObject *mp)
2019{
2020 PyObject *v;
2021 Py_ssize_t i, j;
2022 PyDictKeyEntry *ep;
2023 Py_ssize_t size, n, offset;
2024 PyObject **value_ptr;
2025
2026 again:
2027 n = mp->ma_used;
2028 v = PyList_New(n);
2029 if (v == NULL)
2030 return NULL;
2031 if (n != mp->ma_used) {
2032 /* Durnit. The allocations caused the dict to resize.
2033 * Just start over, this shouldn't normally happen.
2034 */
2035 Py_DECREF(v);
2036 goto again;
2037 }
2038 ep = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
2039 size = mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries;
2040 if (mp->ma_values) {
2041 value_ptr = mp->ma_values;
2042 offset = sizeof(PyObject *);
2043 }
2044 else {
2045 value_ptr = &ep[0].me_value;
2046 offset = sizeof(PyDictKeyEntry);
2047 }
2048 for (i = 0, j = 0; i < size; i++) {
2049 if (*value_ptr != NULL) {
2050 PyObject *key = ep[i].me_key;
2051 Py_INCREF(key);
2052 PyList_SET_ITEM(v, j, key);
2053 j++;
2054 }
2055 value_ptr = (PyObject **)(((char *)value_ptr) + offset);
2056 }
2057 assert(j == n);
2058 return v;
2059}
2060
2061static PyObject *
2062dict_values(PyDictObject *mp)
2063{
2064 PyObject *v;
2065 Py_ssize_t i, j;
2066 PyDictKeyEntry *ep;

2070 again:

2073 if (v == NULL)
2074 return NULL;
2075 if (n != mp->ma_used) {
2076 /* Durnit. The allocations caused the dict to resize.
2077 * Just start over, this shouldn't normally happen.
2078 */
2079 Py_DECREF(v);
2080 goto again;
2081 }
2082 ep = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
2083 size = mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries;

2086 offset = sizeof(PyObject *);
2087 }
2088 else {

2090 offset = sizeof(PyDictKeyEntry);
2091 }

2093 PyObject *value = *value_ptr;
2094 value_ptr = (PyObject **)(((char *)value_ptr) + offset);
2095 if (value != NULL) {
2096 Py_INCREF(value);
2097 PyList_SET_ITEM(v, j, value);

2105static PyObject *
2106dict_items(PyDictObject *mp)
2107{
2108 PyObject *v;
2109 Py_ssize_t i, j, n;
2110 Py_ssize_t size, offset;

2112 PyDictKeyEntry *ep;
2113 PyObject **value_ptr;
2114
2115 /* Preallocate the list of tuples, to avoid allocations during
2116 * the loop over the items, which could trigger GC, which
2117 * could resize the dict. :-(
2118 */
2119 again:
2120 n = mp->ma_used;

2122 if (v == NULL)
2123 return NULL;
2124 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
2125 item = PyTuple_New(2);
2126 if (item == NULL) {
2127 Py_DECREF(v);
2128 return NULL;
2129 }
2130 PyList_SET_ITEM(v, i, item);
2131 }
2132 if (n != mp->ma_used) {
2133 /* Durnit. The allocations caused the dict to resize.
2134 * Just start over, this shouldn't normally happen.
2135 */
2136 Py_DECREF(v);
2137 goto again;
2138 }
2139 /* Nothing we do below makes any function calls. */
2140 ep = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
2141 size = mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries;
2142 if (mp->ma_values) {
2143 value_ptr = mp->ma_values;
2144 offset = sizeof(PyObject *);
2145 }
2146 else {
2147 value_ptr = &ep[0].me_value;
2148 offset = sizeof(PyDictKeyEntry);
2149 }

2151 PyObject *value = *value_ptr;
2152 value_ptr = (PyObject **)(((char *)value_ptr) + offset);
2153 if (value != NULL) {
2154 key = ep[i].me_key;
2155 item = PyList_GET_ITEM(v, j);
2156 Py_INCREF(key);
2157 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(item, 0, key);
2158 Py_INCREF(value);

2221/* Update unconditionally replaces existing items.
2222 Merge has a 3rd argument 'override'; if set, it acts like Update,
2223 otherwise it leaves existing items unchanged.
2224
2225 PyDict_{Update,Merge} update/merge from a mapping object.
2226
2227 PyDict_MergeFromSeq2 updates/merges from any iterable object
2228 producing iterable objects of length 2.
2229*/
2230
2231int
2232PyDict_MergeFromSeq2(PyObject *d, PyObject *seq2, int override)
2233{
2234 PyObject *it; /* iter(seq2) */
2235 Py_ssize_t i; /* index into seq2 of current element */
2236 PyObject *item; /* seq2[i] */
2237 PyObject *fast; /* item as a 2-tuple or 2-list */
2238
2239 assert(d != NULL);
2240 assert(PyDict_Check(d));
2241 assert(seq2 != NULL);
2242
2243 it = PyObject_GetIter(seq2);
2244 if (it == NULL)
2245 return -1;
2246
2247 for (i = 0; ; ++i) {
2248 PyObject *key, *value;
2249 Py_ssize_t n;
2250
2251 fast = NULL;
2252 item = PyIter_Next(it);
2253 if (item == NULL) {
2254 if (PyErr_Occurred())
2255 goto Fail;
2256 break;
2257 }
2258
2259 /* Convert item to sequence, and verify length 2. */
2260 fast = PySequence_Fast(item, "");
2261 if (fast == NULL) {
2262 if (PyErr_ExceptionMatches(PyExc_TypeError))
2263 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
2264 "cannot convert dictionary update "
2265 "sequence element #%zd to a sequence",
2266 i);
2267 goto Fail;
2268 }
2269 n = PySequence_Fast_GET_SIZE(fast);
2270 if (n != 2) {
2271 PyErr_Format(PyExc_ValueError,
2272 "dictionary update sequence element #%zd "
2273 "has length %zd; 2 is required",
2274 i, n);
2275 goto Fail;
2276 }
2277
2278 /* Update/merge with this (key, value) pair. */
2279 key = PySequence_Fast_GET_ITEM(fast, 0);
2280 value = PySequence_Fast_GET_ITEM(fast, 1);
2281 Py_INCREF(key);
2282 Py_INCREF(value);
2283 if (override || PyDict_GetItem(d, key) == NULL) {
2284 int status = PyDict_SetItem(d, key, value);
2285 if (status < 0) {
2286 Py_DECREF(key);
2287 Py_DECREF(value);
2288 goto Fail;
2289 }
2290 }
2291 Py_DECREF(key);
2292 Py_DECREF(value);
2293 Py_DECREF(fast);
2294 Py_DECREF(item);
2295 }
2296
2297 i = 0;
2298 assert(_PyDict_CheckConsistency((PyDictObject *)d));
2299 goto Return;
2300Fail:
2301 Py_XDECREF(item);
2302 Py_XDECREF(fast);
2303 i = -1;
2304Return:
2305 Py_DECREF(it);
2306 return Py_SAFE_DOWNCAST(i, Py_ssize_t, int);
2307}

2309static int
2310dict_merge(PyObject *a, PyObject *b, int override)
2311{
2312 PyDictObject *mp, *other;
2313 Py_ssize_t i, n;
2314 PyDictKeyEntry *entry, *ep0;
2315
2316 assert(0 <= override && override <= 2);
2317
2318 /* We accept for the argument either a concrete dictionary object,
2319 * or an abstract "mapping" object. For the former, we can do
2320 * things quite efficiently. For the latter, we only require that
2321 * PyMapping_Keys() and PyObject_GetItem() be supported.
2322 */
2323 if (a == NULL || !PyDict_Check(a) || b == NULL) {
2324 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
2325 return -1;
2326 }
2327 mp = (PyDictObject*)a;
2328 if (PyDict_Check(b)) {
2329 other = (PyDictObject*)b;
2330 if (other == mp || other->ma_used == 0)
2331 /* a.update(a) or a.update({}); nothing to do */
2332 return 0;
2333 if (mp->ma_used == 0)
2334 /* Since the target dict is empty, PyDict_GetItem()
2335 * always returns NULL. Setting override to 1
2336 * skips the unnecessary test.
2337 */
2338 override = 1;
2339 /* Do one big resize at the start, rather than
2340 * incrementally resizing as we insert new items. Expect
2341 * that there will be no (or few) overlapping keys.
2342 */
2343 if (USABLE_FRACTION(mp->ma_keys->dk_size) < other->ma_used) {
2344 if (dictresize(mp, ESTIMATE_SIZE(mp->ma_used + other->ma_used))) {
2345 return -1;
2346 }
2347 }
2348 ep0 = DK_ENTRIES(other->ma_keys);
2349 for (i = 0, n = other->ma_keys->dk_nentries; i < n; i++) {
2350 PyObject *key, *value;
2351 Py_hash_t hash;
2352 entry = &ep0[i];
2353 key = entry->me_key;
2354 hash = entry->me_hash;
2355 if (other->ma_values)
2356 value = other->ma_values[i];
2357 else
2358 value = entry->me_value;
2359
2360 if (value != NULL) {
2361 int err = 0;
2362 Py_INCREF(key);
2363 Py_INCREF(value);
2364 if (override == 1)
2365 err = insertdict(mp, key, hash, value);
2366 else if (_PyDict_GetItem_KnownHash(a, key, hash) == NULL) {
2367 if (PyErr_Occurred()) {
2368 Py_DECREF(value);
2369 Py_DECREF(key);
2370 return -1;
2371 }
2372 err = insertdict(mp, key, hash, value);
2373 }
2374 else if (override != 0) {
2375 _PyErr_SetKeyError(key);
2376 Py_DECREF(value);
2377 Py_DECREF(key);
2378 return -1;
2379 }
2380 Py_DECREF(value);
2381 Py_DECREF(key);
2382 if (err != 0)
2383 return -1;
2384
2385 if (n != other->ma_keys->dk_nentries) {
2386 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,
2387 "dict mutated during update");
2388 return -1;
2389 }
2390 }
2391 }
2392 }
2393 else {
2394 /* Do it the generic, slower way */
2395 PyObject *keys = PyMapping_Keys(b);
2396 PyObject *iter;
2397 PyObject *key, *value;
2398 int status;
2399
2400 if (keys == NULL)
2401 /* Docstring says this is equivalent to E.keys() so
2402 * if E doesn't have a .keys() method we want
2403 * AttributeError to percolate up. Might as well
2404 * do the same for any other error.
2405 */
2406 return -1;
2407
2408 iter = PyObject_GetIter(keys);
2409 Py_DECREF(keys);
2410 if (iter == NULL)
2411 return -1;
2412
2413 for (key = PyIter_Next(iter); key; key = PyIter_Next(iter)) {
2414 if (override != 1 && PyDict_GetItem(a, key) != NULL) {
2415 if (override != 0) {
2416 _PyErr_SetKeyError(key);
2417 Py_DECREF(key);
2418 Py_DECREF(iter);
2419 return -1;
2420 }
2421 Py_DECREF(key);
2422 continue;
2423 }
2424 value = PyObject_GetItem(b, key);
2425 if (value == NULL) {
2426 Py_DECREF(iter);
2427 Py_DECREF(key);
2428 return -1;
2429 }
2430 status = PyDict_SetItem(a, key, value);
2431 Py_DECREF(key);
2432 Py_DECREF(value);
2433 if (status < 0) {
2434 Py_DECREF(iter);
2435 return -1;
2436 }
2437 }
2438 Py_DECREF(iter);
2439 if (PyErr_Occurred())
2440 /* Iterator completed, via error */
2441 return -1;
2442 }
2443 assert(_PyDict_CheckConsistency((PyDictObject *)a));
2444 return 0;
2445}

2558/* Return 1 if dicts equal, 0 if not, -1 if error.
2559 * Gets out as soon as any difference is detected.
2560 * Uses only Py_EQ comparison.
2561 */
2562static int
2563dict_equal(PyDictObject *a, PyDictObject *b)
2564{
2565 Py_ssize_t i;
2566
2567 if (a->ma_used != b->ma_used)
2568 /* can't be equal if # of entries differ */
2569 return 0;
2570 /* Same # of entries -- check all of 'em. Exit early on any diff. */
2571 for (i = 0; i < a->ma_keys->dk_nentries; i++) {
2572 PyDictKeyEntry *ep = &DK_ENTRIES(a->ma_keys)[i];
2573 PyObject *aval;
2574 if (a->ma_values)
2575 aval = a->ma_values[i];
2576 else
2577 aval = ep->me_value;
2578 if (aval != NULL) {
2579 int cmp;
2580 PyObject *bval;
2581 PyObject *key = ep->me_key;
2582 /* temporarily bump aval's refcount to ensure it stays
2583 alive until we're done with it */
2584 Py_INCREF(aval);
2585 /* ditto for key */
2586 Py_INCREF(key);
2587 /* reuse the known hash value */
2588 b->ma_keys->dk_lookup(b, key, ep->me_hash, &bval);
2589 if (bval == NULL) {
2590 Py_DECREF(key);
2591 Py_DECREF(aval);
2592 if (PyErr_Occurred())
2593 return -1;
2594 return 0;
2595 }
2596 cmp = PyObject_RichCompareBool(aval, bval, Py_EQ);
2597 Py_DECREF(key);
2598 Py_DECREF(aval);
2599 if (cmp <= 0) /* error or not equal */
2600 return cmp;
2601 }
2602 }
2603 return 1;
2604}

2809dict_pop(PyDictObject *mp, PyObject *args)
2810{
2811 PyObject *key, *deflt = NULL;
2812
2813 if(!PyArg_UnpackTuple(args, "pop", 1, 2, &key, &deflt))

2818
2819static PyObject *
2820dict_popitem(PyDictObject *mp)
2821{
2822 Py_ssize_t i, j;
2823 PyDictKeyEntry *ep0, *ep;
2824 PyObject *res;
2825
2826 /* Allocate the result tuple before checking the size. Believe it
2827 * or not, this allocation could trigger a garbage collection which
2828 * could empty the dict, so if we checked the size first and that
2829 * happened, the result would be an infinite loop (searching for an
2830 * entry that no longer exists). Note that the usual popitem()
2831 * idiom is "while d: k, v = d.popitem()". so needing to throw the
2832 * tuple away if the dict *is* empty isn't a significant
2833 * inefficiency -- possible, but unlikely in practice.
2834 */
2835 res = PyTuple_New(2);
2836 if (res == NULL)
2837 return NULL;
2838 if (mp->ma_used == 0) {
2839 Py_DECREF(res);
2840 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_KeyError,
2841 "popitem(): dictionary is empty");
2842 return NULL;
2843 }
2844 /* Convert split table to combined table */
2845 if (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup == lookdict_split) {
2846 if (dictresize(mp, DK_SIZE(mp->ma_keys))) {
2847 Py_DECREF(res);
2848 return NULL;
2849 }
2850 }
2851 ENSURE_ALLOWS_DELETIONS(mp);
2852
2853 /* Pop last item */
2854 ep0 = DK_ENTRIES(mp->ma_keys);
2855 i = mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries - 1;
2856 while (i >= 0 && ep0[i].me_value == NULL) {
2857 i--;
2858 }
2859 assert(i >= 0);
2860
2861 ep = &ep0[i];
2862 j = lookdict_index(mp->ma_keys, ep->me_hash, i);
2863 assert(j >= 0);
2864 assert(dk_get_index(mp->ma_keys, j) == i);
2865 dk_set_index(mp->ma_keys, j, DKIX_DUMMY);
2866
2867 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(res, 0, ep->me_key);
2868 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(res, 1, ep->me_value);
2869 ep->me_key = NULL;
2870 ep->me_value = NULL;
2871 /* We can't dk_usable++ since there is DKIX_DUMMY in indices */
2872 mp->ma_keys->dk_nentries = i;
2873 mp->ma_used--;
2874 mp->ma_version_tag = DICT_NEXT_VERSION();
2875 assert(_PyDict_CheckConsistency(mp));
2876 return res;
2877}
2878
2879static int
2880dict_traverse(PyObject *op, visitproc visit, void *arg)
2881{
2882 PyDictObject *mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
2883 PyDictKeysObject *keys = mp->ma_keys;
2884 PyDictKeyEntry *entries = DK_ENTRIES(keys);
2885 Py_ssize_t i, n = keys->dk_nentries;
2886
2887 if (keys->dk_lookup == lookdict) {
2888 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
2889 if (entries[i].me_value != NULL) {
2890 Py_VISIT(entries[i].me_value);
2891 Py_VISIT(entries[i].me_key);
2892 }
2893 }
2894 }
2895 else {
2896 if (mp->ma_values != NULL) {
2897 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
2898 Py_VISIT(mp->ma_values[i]);
2899 }
2900 }
2901 else {
2902 for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
2903 Py_VISIT(entries[i].me_value);
2904 }
2905 }
2906 }
2907 return 0;
2908}

2919Py_ssize_t
2920_PyDict_SizeOf(PyDictObject *mp)
2921{
2922 Py_ssize_t size, usable, res;
2923
2924 size = DK_SIZE(mp->ma_keys);
2925 usable = USABLE_FRACTION(size);
2926
2927 res = _PyObject_SIZE(Py_TYPE(mp));
2928 if (mp->ma_values)
2929 res += usable * sizeof(PyObject*);
2930 /* If the dictionary is split, the keys portion is accounted-for
2931 in the type object. */
2932 if (mp->ma_keys->dk_refcnt == 1)
2933 res += (sizeof(PyDictKeysObject)
2934 - Py_MEMBER_SIZE(PyDictKeysObject, dk_indices)
2935 + DK_IXSIZE(mp->ma_keys) * size
2936 + sizeof(PyDictKeyEntry) * usable);
2937 return res;
2938}

2945 + DK_IXSIZE(keys) * DK_SIZE(keys)
2946 + USABLE_FRACTION(DK_SIZE(keys)) * sizeof(PyDictKeyEntry));
2947}

3020/* Return 1 if `key` is in dict `op`, 0 if not, and -1 on error. */
3021int
3022PyDict_Contains(PyObject *op, PyObject *key)
3023{
3024 Py_hash_t hash;
3025 Py_ssize_t ix;
3026 PyDictObject *mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
3027 PyObject *value;
3028
3029 if (!PyUnicode_CheckExact(key) ||
3030 (hash = ((PyASCIIObject *) key)->hash) == -1) {
3031 hash = PyObject_Hash(key);
3032 if (hash == -1)
3033 return -1;
3034 }
3035 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &value);
3036 if (ix == DKIX_ERROR)
3037 return -1;
3038 return (ix != DKIX_EMPTY && value != NULL);
3039}
3040
3041/* Internal version of PyDict_Contains used when the hash value is already known */
3042int
3043_PyDict_Contains(PyObject *op, PyObject *key, Py_hash_t hash)
3044{
3045 PyDictObject *mp = (PyDictObject *)op;
3046 PyObject *value;
3047 Py_ssize_t ix;
3048
3049 ix = (mp->ma_keys->dk_lookup)(mp, key, hash, &value);
3050 if (ix == DKIX_ERROR)
3051 return -1;
3052 return (ix != DKIX_EMPTY && value != NULL);
3053}

3315static PyObject*
3316dictiter_iternextkey(dictiterobject *di)
3317{
3318 PyObject *key;
3319 Py_ssize_t i;
3320 PyDictKeysObject *k;
3321 PyDictObject *d = di->di_dict;
3322
3323 if (d == NULL)
3324 return NULL;
3325 assert (PyDict_Check(d));
3326
3327 if (di->di_used != d->ma_used) {
3328 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,

3330 di->di_used = -1; /* Make this state sticky */
3331 return NULL;

3333

3335 k = d->ma_keys;
3336 assert(i >= 0);
3337 if (d->ma_values) {

3339 goto fail;
3340 key = DK_ENTRIES(k)[i].me_key;
3341 assert(d->ma_values[i] != NULL);
3342 }

3350 if (i >= n)

3352 key = entry_ptr->me_key;
3353 }
3354 di->di_pos = i+1;
3355 di->len--;

3479static PyObject *
3480dictiter_iternextitem(dictiterobject *di)
3481{
3482 PyObject *key, *value, *result;
3483 Py_ssize_t i;
3484 PyDictObject *d = di->di_dict;
3485
3486 if (d == NULL)
3487 return NULL;
3488 assert (PyDict_Check(d));
3489
3490 if (di->di_used != d->ma_used) {
3491 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError,
3492 "dictionary changed size during iteration");
3493 di->di_used = -1; /* Make this state sticky */
3494 return NULL;
3495 }
3496
3497 i = di->di_pos;
3498 assert(i >= 0);
3499 if (d->ma_values) {
3500 if (i >= d->ma_used)
3501 goto fail;
3502 key = DK_ENTRIES(d->ma_keys)[i].me_key;
3503 value = d->ma_values[i];
3504 assert(value != NULL);
3505 }
3506 else {
3507 Py_ssize_t n = d->ma_keys->dk_nentries;
3508 PyDictKeyEntry *entry_ptr = &DK_ENTRIES(d->ma_keys)[i];
3509 while (i < n && entry_ptr->me_value == NULL) {
3510 entry_ptr++;
3511 i++;
3512 }
3513 if (i >= n)
3514 goto fail;
3515 key = entry_ptr->me_key;
3516 value = entry_ptr->me_value;
3517 }
3518 di->di_pos = i+1;
3519 di->len--;
3520 Py_INCREF(key);
3521 Py_INCREF(value);
3522 result = di->di_result;
3523 if (Py_REFCNT(result) == 1) {
3524 PyObject *oldkey = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(result, 0);
3525 PyObject *oldvalue = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(result, 1);
3526 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(result, 0, key); /* steals reference */
3527 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(result, 1, value); /* steals reference */
3528 Py_INCREF(result);
3529 Py_DECREF(oldkey);
3530 Py_DECREF(oldvalue);
3531 }
3532 else {
3533 result = PyTuple_New(2);
3534 if (result == NULL)
3535 return NULL;
3536 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(result, 0, key); /* steals reference */
3537 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(result, 1, value); /* steals reference */
3538 }
3539 return result;
3540
3541fail:
3542 di->di_dict = NULL;
3543 Py_DECREF(d);
3544 return NULL;
3545}

3580
3581static PyObject *
3582dictiter_reduce(dictiterobject *di)
3583{
3584 PyObject *list;
3585 dictiterobject tmp;
3586
3587 list = PyList_New(0);
3588 if (!list)
3589 return NULL;
3590
3591 /* copy the itertor state */
3592 tmp = *di;
3593 Py_XINCREF(tmp.di_dict);
3594
3595 /* iterate the temporary into a list */
3596 for(;;) {
3597 PyObject *element = 0;
3598 if (Py_TYPE(di) == &PyDictIterItem_Type)
3599 element = dictiter_iternextitem(&tmp);
3600 else if (Py_TYPE(di) == &PyDictIterKey_Type)
3601 element = dictiter_iternextkey(&tmp);
3602 else if (Py_TYPE(di) == &PyDictIterValue_Type)
3603 element = dictiter_iternextvalue(&tmp);
3604 else
3605 assert(0);
3606 if (element) {
3607 if (PyList_Append(list, element)) {
3608 Py_DECREF(element);
3609 Py_DECREF(list);
3610 Py_XDECREF(tmp.di_dict);
3611 return NULL;
3612 }
3613 Py_DECREF(element);
3614 } else
3615 break;
3616 }
3617 Py_XDECREF(tmp.di_dict);
3618 /* check for error */
3619 if (tmp.di_dict != NULL) {
3620 /* we have an error */
3621 Py_DECREF(list);
3622 return NULL;
3623 }
3624 return Py_BuildValue("N(N)", _PyObject_GetBuiltin("iter"), list);
3625}

3658PyObject *
3659_PyDictView_New(PyObject *dict, PyTypeObject *type)
3660{
3661 _PyDictViewObject *dv;
3662 if (dict == NULL) {
3663 PyErr_BadInternalCall();
3664 return NULL;
3665 }
3666 if (!PyDict_Check(dict)) {
3667 /* XXX Get rid of this restriction later */
3668 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3669 "%s() requires a dict argument, not '%s'",
3670 type->tp_name, dict->ob_type->tp_name);
3671 return NULL;
3672 }
3673 dv = PyObject_GC_New(_PyDictViewObject, type);
3674 if (dv == NULL)
3675 return NULL;
3676 Py_INCREF(dict);
3677 dv->dv_dict = (PyDictObject *)dict;
3678 _PyObject_GC_TRACK(dv);
3679 return (PyObject *)dv;
3680}

3682/* TODO(guido): The views objects are not complete:
3683
3684 * support more set operations
3685 * support arbitrary mappings?
3686 - either these should be static or exported in dictobject.h
3687 - if public then they should probably be in builtins
3688*/
3689
3690/* Return 1 if self is a subset of other, iterating over self;
3691 0 if not; -1 if an error occurred. */
3692static int
3693all_contained_in(PyObject *self, PyObject *other)
3694{
3695 PyObject *iter = PyObject_GetIter(self);
3696 int ok = 1;
3697
3698 if (iter == NULL)
3699 return -1;
3700 for (;;) {
3701 PyObject *next = PyIter_Next(iter);
3702 if (next == NULL) {
3703 if (PyErr_Occurred())
3704 ok = -1;
3705 break;
3706 }
3707 ok = PySequence_Contains(other, next);
3708 Py_DECREF(next);
3709 if (ok <= 0)
3710 break;
3711 }
3712 Py_DECREF(iter);
3713 return ok;
3714}
3715
3716static PyObject *
3717dictview_richcompare(PyObject *self, PyObject *other, int op)
3718{
3719 Py_ssize_t len_self, len_other;
3720 int ok;
3721 PyObject *result;
3722
3723 assert(self != NULL);
3724 assert(PyDictViewSet_Check(self));
3725 assert(other != NULL);
3726
3727 if (!PyAnySet_Check(other) && !PyDictViewSet_Check(other))
3728 Py_RETURN_NOTIMPLEMENTED;
3729
3730 len_self = PyObject_Size(self);
3731 if (len_self < 0)
3732 return NULL;
3733 len_other = PyObject_Size(other);
3734 if (len_other < 0)
3735 return NULL;
3736
3737 ok = 0;
3738 switch(op) {
3739
3740 case Py_NE:
3741 case Py_EQ:
3742 if (len_self == len_other)
3743 ok = all_contained_in(self, other);
3744 if (op == Py_NE && ok >= 0)
3745 ok = !ok;
3746 break;
3747
3748 case Py_LT:
3749 if (len_self < len_other)
3750 ok = all_contained_in(self, other);
3751 break;
3752
3753 case Py_LE:
3754 if (len_self <= len_other)
3755 ok = all_contained_in(self, other);
3756 break;
3757
3758 case Py_GT:
3759 if (len_self > len_other)
3760 ok = all_contained_in(other, self);
3761 break;
3762
3763 case Py_GE:
3764 if (len_self >= len_other)
3765 ok = all_contained_in(other, self);
3766 break;
3767
3768 }
3769 if (ok < 0)
3770 return NULL;
3771 result = ok ? Py_True : Py_False;
3772 Py_INCREF(result);
3773 return result;
3774}

3783 if (seq == NULL)
3784 return NULL;
3785
3786 result = PyUnicode_FromFormat("%s(%R)", Py_TYPE(dv)->tp_name, seq);
3787 Py_DECREF(seq);
3788 return result;
3789}

3920static PyObject*
3921dictviews_isdisjoint(PyObject *self, PyObject *other)
3922{
3923 PyObject *it;
3924 PyObject *item = NULL;
3925
3926 if (self == other) {
3927 if (dictview_len((_PyDictViewObject *)self) == 0)
3928 Py_RETURN_TRUE;
3929 else
3930 Py_RETURN_FALSE;
3931 }
3932
3933 /* Iterate over the shorter object (only if other is a set,
3934 * because PySequence_Contains may be expensive otherwise): */
3935 if (PyAnySet_Check(other) || PyDictViewSet_Check(other)) {
3936 Py_ssize_t len_self = dictview_len((_PyDictViewObject *)self);
3937 Py_ssize_t len_other = PyObject_Size(other);
3938 if (len_other == -1)
3939 return NULL;
3940
3941 if ((len_other > len_self)) {
3942 PyObject *tmp = other;
3943 other = self;
3944 self = tmp;
3945 }
3946 }
3947
3948 it = PyObject_GetIter(other);
3949 if (it == NULL)
3950 return NULL;
3951
3952 while ((item = PyIter_Next(it)) != NULL) {
3953 int contains = PySequence_Contains(self, item);
3954 Py_DECREF(item);
3955 if (contains == -1) {
3956 Py_DECREF(it);
3957 return NULL;
3958 }
3959
3960 if (contains) {
3961 Py_DECREF(it);
3962 Py_RETURN_FALSE;
3963 }
3964 }
3965 Py_DECREF(it);
3966 if (PyErr_Occurred())
3967 return NULL; /* PyIter_Next raised an exception. */
3968 Py_RETURN_TRUE;
3969}

4030static int
4031dictitems_contains(_PyDictViewObject *dv, PyObject *obj)
4032{
4033 int result;
4034 PyObject *key, *value, *found;
4035 if (dv->dv_dict == NULL)
4036 return 0;
4037 if (!PyTuple_Check(obj) || PyTuple_GET_SIZE(obj) != 2)
4038 return 0;
4039 key = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(obj, 0);
4040 value = PyTuple_GET_ITEM(obj, 1);
4041 found = PyDict_GetItemWithError((PyObject *)dv->dv_dict, key);
4042 if (found == NULL) {
4043 if (PyErr_Occurred())
4044 return -1;
4045 return 0;
4046 }
4047 Py_INCREF(found);
4048 result = PyObject_RichCompareBool(value, found, Py_EQ);
4049 Py_DECREF(found);
4050 return result;
4051}

4166};

4187#define CACHED_KEYS(tp) (((PyHeapTypeObject*)tp)->ht_cached_keys)
4188
4189PyObject *
4190PyObject_GenericGetDict(PyObject *obj, void *context)
4191{
4192 PyObject *dict, **dictptr = _PyObject_GetDictPtr(obj);
4193 if (dictptr == NULL) {
4194 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_AttributeError,
4195 "This object has no __dict__");
4196 return NULL;
4197 }
4198 dict = *dictptr;
4199 if (dict == NULL) {
4200 PyTypeObject *tp = Py_TYPE(obj);
4201 if ((tp->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE) && CACHED_KEYS(tp)) {
4202 DK_INCREF(CACHED_KEYS(tp));
4203 *dictptr = dict = new_dict_with_shared_keys(CACHED_KEYS(tp));
4204 }
4205 else {
4206 *dictptr = dict = PyDict_New();
4207 }
4208 }
4209 Py_XINCREF(dict);
4210 return dict;
4211}
4212
4213int
4214_PyObjectDict_SetItem(PyTypeObject *tp, PyObject **dictptr,
4215 PyObject *key, PyObject *value)
4216{
4217 PyObject *dict;
4218 int res;
4219 PyDictKeysObject *cached;
4220
4221 assert(dictptr != NULL);
4222 if ((tp->tp_flags & Py_TPFLAGS_HEAPTYPE) && (cached = CACHED_KEYS(tp))) {
4223 assert(dictptr != NULL);
4224 dict = *dictptr;
4225 if (dict == NULL) {
4226 DK_INCREF(cached);
4227 dict = new_dict_with_shared_keys(cached);
4228 if (dict == NULL)
4229 return -1;
4230 *dictptr = dict;
4231 }
4232 if (value == NULL) {
4233 res = PyDict_DelItem(dict, key);
4234 // Since key sharing dict doesn't allow deletion, PyDict_DelItem()
4235 // always converts dict to combined form.
4236 if ((cached = CACHED_KEYS(tp)) != NULL) {
4237 CACHED_KEYS(tp) = NULL;
4238 DK_DECREF(cached);
4239 }
4240 }
4241 else {
4242 int was_shared = (cached == ((PyDictObject *)dict)->ma_keys);
4243 res = PyDict_SetItem(dict, key, value);
4244 if (was_shared &&
4245 (cached = CACHED_KEYS(tp)) != NULL &&
4246 cached != ((PyDictObject *)dict)->ma_keys) {
4247 /* PyDict_SetItem() may call dictresize and convert split table
4248 * into combined table. In such case, convert it to split
4249 * table again and update type's shared key only when this is
4250 * the only dict sharing key with the type.
4251 *
4252 * This is to allow using shared key in class like this:
4253 *
4254 * class C:
4255 * def __init__(self):
4256 * # one dict resize happens
4257 * self.a, self.b, self.c = 1, 2, 3
4258 * self.d, self.e, self.f = 4, 5, 6
4259 * a = C()
4260 */
4261 if (cached->dk_refcnt == 1) {
4262 CACHED_KEYS(tp) = make_keys_shared(dict);
4263 }
4264 else {
4265 CACHED_KEYS(tp) = NULL;
4266 }
4267 DK_DECREF(cached);
4268 if (CACHED_KEYS(tp) == NULL && PyErr_Occurred())
4269 return -1;
4270 }
4271 }
4272 } else {
4273 dict = *dictptr;
4274 if (dict == NULL) {
4275 dict = PyDict_New();
4276 if (dict == NULL)
4277 return -1;
4278 *dictptr = dict;
4279 }
4280 if (value == NULL) {
4281 res = PyDict_DelItem(dict, key);
4282 } else {
4283 res = PyDict_SetItem(dict, key, value);
4284 }
4285 }
4286 return res;
4287}
